ETFs also offer a wide range of funds, which is great, but it's essential for investors to assess whether these stated benefits truly exist and to what extent. For our analysis, we'll focus on the ETF IHF and compare it with the top 10 holdings to determine if owning a single ETF matches owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and whether there might be better configurations for a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

Given the complexity, we'll include only the top 10 holdings that account for 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Here they are and their respective percentages:

[REWRITE]To gauge how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we'll use their current asset percentages, normalized to 100%, to calculate contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return. The calculations are shown below:

The chart reveals that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings yields a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, a 16% increase, and a Beta that is .12 lower than the ETF. These findings suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer higher returns with lower Beta. However, the statistical difference between these two portfolios remains uncertain.

To assess if these portfolios are statistically different, we'll determine the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

In "Dream-Land", Edgar Allan Poe uses the term "Thulé" twice, a reference that's traced back to Virgil. Virgil employed this term to denote an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world. While Virgil's usage is certain, a more contemporary source is equally noteworthy - Poe's familiarity with the works of German authors like Goethe. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon", highlights similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, suggesting Poe was indeed imitating Goethe's style. Goethe is celebrated for his poetic drama "Faust", published in two parts, with the second part (containing a poem titled "The King of Thule") published in the year of his death, 1832. This poem tells the story of a king who loses his queen and subsequently his will to live, echoing the despairing speaker of "Dream-Land". "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces, with Poe's poem mirroring Goethe's dark narrative. Poe also references "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum", further cementing this connection. This textual borrowing underscores Poe's admiration for Goethe, a writer he would have known through his respect for Tennyson and the widespread reproductions of German literature in the 19th century.

Under California law, a customer injured by slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could potentially be awarded punitive damages if they can show that the store manager acted with malice. To succeed, the injured party must prove two things: that the defendant’s actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result, and that the conduct was despicable. In this case, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, can argue that the manager, Paul Martin, should have known about the potential harm of not cleaning the spill because multiple customers were injured by slips months before Palmer's accident. Despite this knowledge, Martin failed to clean the spill, which Palmer can argue was despicable. While this argument might not be as strong, it is still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin did not take appropriate actions to maintain the store's safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee, Rich Wayne, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about the applesauce spill. Martin replied that he was on dinner break and didn't have time to deal with customer complaints. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin about the spill, and he responded similarly. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights when the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in an Islam course at CBC, where the central debate was whether or not Islam is inherently hostile. This question, I believe, is even more pertinent today than it was then. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I've witnessed a shift in mainstream media's perception of Islam and extremism, ranging from outright hostility to extreme tolerance. I'm not sure that, in 2001, an American presidential candidate with a Muslim heritage, like Barack Obama, could have been plausible.

The Prophet's biography captivates me, as it seems to portray a Muhammad whose character contradicts the historical accounts I've read. Traditionally, Muhammad was depicted as a conqueror who forced conversions upon captured tribes. In the biography, however, he is portrayed as a misunderstood martyr, who humbly proselytized until people spontaneously embraced his teachings. This narrative seems to diminish Muhammad's miraculous deeds, paralleling those of Jesus, and may even aim to appropriate the essence of Christ's life and teachings through Muhammad.

Additionally, many stories in the biography appear to serve as proof of personal conversions, often recounted through several intermediaries. This storytelling technique, while intended to authenticate the stories,降低s their credibility, making them seem even more dubious.

What troubles me the most is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a divine, humble, and wise figure. Historical evidence suggests a different narrative, one where Muhammad's rise to power was not characterized by gentleness and humility. I can't help but wonder if contemporary Muslims are aware of the true background behind Muhammad's ascent.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus, as they existed during his lifetime, have long since been left behind in the evolution of Christian thought. When we examine this history in broad strokes, we see a clear trend of Christianity moving increasingly away from its origins. Today’s world is marked by an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional individuals persist and may attempt to resist new ideas, their influence on the whole may not be significant. Among Christians, a historical consciousness will likely grow in future years. There will be a desire to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from those originally intended by the religion’s namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable: there will be a notable shift in the trend of Christian history. A movement will grow, removing layers of doctrine one by one, as if the clock were turning backward, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity remains. When this trend reaches the United States and Europe, it will influence masses to worship as if they were living during Jesus’ time, following his teachings exclusively. The church will remain strong to guide this process, but the theological clock having moved backward will lead to greater uniformity of belief and practice, reducing diversity. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, we will see more similarities than differences. History is filled with great reversals. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire but later became part of the empire itself. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The forthcoming great reversion in Christian history will play out by undoing history in search of the source and reducing diversity. A key factor in making this process possible will be interpreting Jesus’ words metaphorically rather than literally. But what has changed since Jesus’ lifetime? Looking back in history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were core elements of the religion when the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united in spirit, dividing into various groups such as Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of ordinary people.

I think The Jungle reveals the inherent greed and self-centeredness of humans, with a constant drive to improve our own lives at the expense of others. The book demonstrates this through various aspects, prominently the factory owners and managers. Their sole goal is to expand and increase their businesses without regard for anyone or anything in their path, as Upton Sinclair illustrates, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." They show no concern for the pollution and the suffering of animals and people alike. The workers, too, are viewed as mere tools to fuel their profits, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They exploit their employees, forcing them to work long hours and lay them off without notice or compensation. In those times, there were few, if any, laws to protect workers' safety, allowing managers and owners to operate with impunity, pushing their workers to produce more in harsh conditions. The book hints that the workers accepted their fate, living and working in such conditions, with no agencies or organizations to assist them. Unions formed, but they often only exploited the workers further. The workers were so mistreated and trapped in the system that they were compared to slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers employ various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers towards significant subjects. Some of these methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes several of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. One technique he uses is pairing unusual adjective-noun combinations to create a certain ambiance around a subject. He also assigns symbolic meanings to colors, which he then employs for this purpose. Fitzgerald frequently employs this technique with numerous colors, such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald builds up symbolic meanings for white/gray and red/pink, which he later uses to evoke particular feelings about crucial subjects.

Fitzgerald associates the meaning of uniformity with white/gray, where white signifies a higher class and gray represents something older and faded. This association is established early in the novel through repeated uses of these colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as "in white" (8), and even Nick wears "white flannels" (41) to Gatsby's party. Tom is in a "white shirt" (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white" (30). The only exceptions are when Nick is forming his initial impressions of Gatsby's party, where the halls are "gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further emphasizes these color meanings by applying them to everyday, unimportant subjects. For instance, Nick travels "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), and Gatsby's party guests have "gray names" (61) on Nick's timetable. Catherine's apartment is described as "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses" (28), and many mundane people or places are described in terms of white or gray. Examples include the "white girlhood" (19) of Jordan and Daisy, the "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, the "gray" (26) Italian child in the railroad, and the "gray old man" (27) selling dogs.

Once Fitzgerald has established these meanings, he employs them to symbolize unimportance or uniformity of certain subjects. The use of white and gray colors to convey this begins with Daisy. After some time with no significant use of these colors, Daisy appears "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster" (74), making her seem less like a character and more like a uniform addition, something Gatsby craves and yearns for. Fitzgerald continues this technique around Daisy to intensify her feeling of uniformity. For example, there is a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), and she is again in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is incredibly fertile, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a significant demand for organic, community-supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations maintaining long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations, as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities, allowing landowners to gain government program benefits while improving habitat quality and creating additional revenue streams through farm tours and educational programs.

Besides filling a profitable niche market, organic farming typically promotes greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, it often incurs higher costs compared to conventional farming, requiring more intensive labor and management for pest and weed control, and soil fertilization without chemicals, and may result in higher losses. Small organic farms also lack the efficiency of scale seen in larger operations. Moreover, practices beneficial to wildlife that are not related to organic farming can also increase labor costs, such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth for specific conditions like edge habitat or patches of open ground. Consequently, a landowner might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality.

The chosen land for this scenario is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It includes chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to the Cleveland National Forest, located in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is currently under review but considers over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterflies, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, like burrowing owls.

This area has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for countless centuries and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production for many decades. I chose this land from a real estate website and researched available government programs to explore cost-mitigation opportunities and wildlife-friendly operations for a small farmer. As a model of what farming this land might entail, I located an organic farm in the same area.

Culture is a crucial factor in any negotiation. It's not just about what a culture is, but also what it's not and what it stands for. Culture isn't uniform or singular; it varies widely. Generalizations like “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” are oversimplifications. While understanding a culture’s common traits is useful, it's more beneficial to grasp how a culture's attitudes influence negotiations. When engaging with a foreign culture, it's natural to relate it to your own and draw comparisons.

Getting to know a foreign culture or mindset can involve exploring its history or recognizing its biases. Rather than trying to change a culture, one must accept it for what it is and work within its norms, especially during negotiation, especially if one has a weaker position. At an “away” negotiation, respecting traditions and beliefs can help overcome cultural barriers and advance the negotiation.

Culture isn't limited to national or international boundaries. Many companies within a nation have their own corporate culture. For instance, a company might prioritize long hours or have a more laid-back schedule. Evidence of corporate culture can be seen in employee attire, communication style, and hiring practices. Some companies encourage employee philanthropy, while others restrict it to approved charities. Even within the same nation, corporate cultures can greatly vary—just compare different companies or regions within the U.S. to see this diversity.

Values are key to understanding a culture, as they provide the 'why' behind cultural behaviors. If saving face or communal harmony is valued, a negotiator won't publicly shame their company or superior to win a negotiation. A negotiator from a culture that values a hard-driven bargain won't settle early. Knowing these cultural values before a negotiation is essential, but understanding your opponent on a personal level can also make the negotiation more effective.

The fool has declared in his heart, "There is no God." This quote is first found in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is the opening of St. Anselm's argument for the existence of God. Similarly, Thomas Aquinas adheres to this belief. Since both arguments aim to validate the same concept, we must assume, for the sake of simplicity, that their shared belief in the Bible's God is correct. This allows us to compare their arguments effectively. However, neither argument truly provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

To elucidate this, let's start with St. Anselm's fundamental argument. Anselm's passage suggests a path to understanding through faith, looking inward for proof. He posits that God's existence is intrinsic to our understanding, making his nonexistence inconceivable. Although this is somewhat abstract, the core idea is that the proof for God lies within our own minds. St. Anselm believes that we don't need external evidence; we only need to examine our inherent knowledge. This concept, often referred to in Christian texts as faith, is quite different from St. Thomas Aquinas' approach.

Thomas Aquinas, conversely, maintains that God's existence can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no reliance on faith. This could be advantageous for evangelism, as it would allow conversion without needing to accept something not proven. Thomas presents five logical arguments for God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument demonstrates that the proof for God lies in logical necessity. For instance, if you know you're missing one puzzle piece and can assemble the rest, you know the features and existence of the missing piece without seeing it.

Around five hundred years before the Common Era, a prince was born who would later be revered as Buddha. He abandoned his worldly life to attain enlightenment, and his teachings shaped the religion of Buddhism, which today is known primarily as Theravada Buddhism. This ancient faith, now more than twenty-five hundred years old, has transformed significantly over time. For instance, in Sri Lanka, a Theravada nation, an annual water-cutting ceremony is held, a tradition that Buddha himself never taught. This illustrates how Theravada Buddhism has evolved, from superficial rituals to its core beliefs.

Throughout history, both the monastic and lay communities of Theravada Buddhism have had to adapt their doctrines due to both internal and external influences, some hostile and others benign. It's crucial to understand these terms. Internal forces are those coming from within the Buddhist community, regardless of one's monastic status, while external forces are from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community due to a negative perception of the faith. Benign forces, on the other hand, may not directly benefit or harm the community but may do so as a side effect.

Let's delve into the core tenets of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in the Triple Gem—the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma consists of the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka includes all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the rules of discipline, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These include concepts such as Anatta, or no soul, Dukkha, which is the inherent suffering in life, and Anicca, the impermanence of all things. Recognizing these teachings can help one escape the cycle of death and rebirth, known as Sansara, and overcome lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five precepts: I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances. Monks follow many more rules. The central teaching is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), that attachment causes suffering, that suffering can be ended, and that the path to enlightenment is the way to overcome suffering.

The United States and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. This competition reached its peak during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States emerged victorious, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Over the years, numerous conflicts occurred between the two nations, with tensions finally easing on the eve of World War I.

This isn't unique to the United States and Mexico; many neighboring nations share such rivalries. Nations sharing borders often find themselves at odds over various interests. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Unlike some Latin American nations, these two countries have traditionally been rivals to the United States, while others have maintained good relations. This rivalry was fueled by religious differences, with Americans and Mexicans clashing over matters of faith and culture, much like the Cold War's ideological struggle between the United States and the Soviet Union. This enmity can be traced back to the distrust between English and Spanish colonial rulers, which both nations inherited.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) record 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during their 57-year rivalry, the majority of which involved territorial issues and border raids. Bandits and outlaws from American towns frequently caused problems, which persisted until both nations imposed military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) argues that the rivalry began to fade as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the United States and American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention (p. 109, p. 110).

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. I was a nurse at the time, having chosen my profession out of a deeply ingrained need for the safety and security I lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I grew older. So, despite my dream of becoming a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing.

However, here I am: 46 years old, single, with no money in the bank, and unable to work. To this day, I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have little left to call my own. I manage to get by, but every day is a struggle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet one truth remains. I could not have survived these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends. And trust me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel very strong at all.

My point is that crises in life, big and small, are inevitable. There are no guarantees, and despite thorough preparation, some things are simply too large to overcome alone.

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop relying solely on big government. Lord knows it's crumbling. Yet, I'd prefer to see Americans learn to trust one another again—learning to help each other and to ask for help—rather than each of us individually scrambling to build our own shelters.

Conservatives in the U.S. talk about "rugged individualism" that built this country, but the truth is, our forefathers' resilience came from compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, prepare. I do. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food, do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove—provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why is it that organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there any limitations or constraints that steer the direction of evolutionary change? As D’Arcy Thompson famously said in 1917, "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms." Yet, mathematical modeling has been applied to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both development and evolution, for instance by Raup and Stanley in 1981. Our research aims to explore how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help unravel the mechanisms behind the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental change. We employed X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters that can be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell shapes to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be visualized as a structure that traverses 360 degrees of space over time, creating coiled turns called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis known as the columella. The speed at which these whorls grow can vary, and each whorl is separated by a continuous line called a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one, known as the body whorl, with the rest of the shell being referred to as the spire. The apex is the tip of the spire, while the opposite end is called the base. The animal exits its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed from different angles: apical (viewing the apex), basal (viewing the base), apertural (viewing the aperture), and abapertural (viewing the aperture from the side). The usual orientation is the apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, begin by viewing the shell from the apical perspective. Determine the starting point of the first suture and draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line, estimating them to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal builds its shell. By tracking the center of each whorl's aperture and its horizontal and vertical radius, the path of the aperture can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical model is established, parameters can be altered to modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained largely unchanged over the past decade. While the nation has made strides towards achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the progress in child and maternal health lags behind, raising questions about the need to bolster the overall health system rather than focusing on specific programs. Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled health workers, now reaching 72%, but this includes traditional practitioners like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions, contributing to high maternal death rates from hemorrhage. Additionally, the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by a health professional has decreased, indicating a concern with postnatal care, which is underreported.

Cesarean-section rates remain low, around 4%, with urban areas having a significantly higher rate of 7% compared to rural areas at 2%. This disparity highlights the inequitable distribution of healthcare services, favoring urban areas. Moreover, there is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting that the poor struggle to access healthcare due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering how to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, a fundamental question arises: should Indonesia focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system? While targeted programs offer clear, manageable objectives and quicker results, there are drawbacks. Heavy investment in one program can lead to funding shortages and resource allocation issues for other areas, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS and its impact on family planning. Furthermore, running multiple, uncoordinated programs can lead to duplicated services and increased administrative burdens.

Victorian novels are renowned for their meticulous attention to detail and their centering on the aristocracy of the era. Two exceptions to this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both works incorporate an element of mystery and a flair for the bizarre, which are atypical of Victorian novels, further enriching the characters and providing insight into their motivations and emotions. In Oliver Twist, this mystery unfolds through dream sequences and dreamlike states, revealing Oliver's inner turmoil, struggles, and growing awareness of his surroundings. For instance, in Chapter 28, Oliver relives the shooting vividly as if in a dream, powerless to control the events or his own reactions. As the shooting sequence unfolds, Oliver is overwhelmed by the lack of control over his circumstances and the constant, numbing pain that accompanies his fear and despair. This reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over his fate, hinting at a growing sense of defeat and resignation, possibly influenced by Fagin's manipulations. In this passage, Dickens masterfully uses these dream sequences to underscore Oliver's vulnerability and helplessness, suggesting a stark contrast between the control he desires and the reality of his situation.

A couple of years ago, I was part of an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. Although I tried to assist them in various subjects, my strengths were in English and reading. I was approached by one of the instructors to help a boy named Adrian, who was struggling with reading. At first, I was puzzled by his peculiar reading issues. He could pronounce some letters perfectly while others he barely recognized. He was of Latino descent, but spoke flawless English. We kept trying until one day his mother visited. She didn’t speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my limited Spanish, we managed to communicate, and that’s when it hit me: Adrian could read, but he didn’t know the English alphabet well. I hope he’s doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue, especially in California schools. It’s not always as clear as we think, even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be a challenge. This problem is well-known, so what can we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was simple: tutoring in English reading, specifically the alphabet and pronunciations. But for children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. A combination of dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, ESL classes, and more is needed.

Firstly, the dual language system is a fantastic idea. It benefits not just Spanish-speaking children, but all students. Research shows that children in such programs outperform their peers academically. Many fear it's a waste of resources, but that's incorrect. If implemented widely, all students would benefit. So, how do we achieve this? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that’s unrealistic. Instead, we could have bilingual special aides or tutors to assist.

From our earliest days, we are told there's something greater than us, beyond what we can grasp. Some of us learn about it in Sunday schools, temples, or explore within. Many accept the religions passed down by our parents, but some reject them outright, believing our egos encompass everything. We may adopt one belief system only to later change our minds. Whatever path we choose reflects our unique spiritual perspectives. We search for light in the dark to guide us from shadows into sunshine.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, rain pounding on the tin roof, our cigarettes burning between us. Gutters gushed water, drowning the plants along the porch edge. He stared into the rain, a look of half-searching, half-remembering. His body had grown gaunt, his hair sparser than I remembered. He remained focused on the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk about how much I would miss him. I hugged him, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the June twilight's rain fall.

My father passed away in December, just days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemo and radiation prolonged his suffering, but kept him alive longer than expected. I couldn't understand the value in that. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago. I didn't want to witness his transition. I remembered him by how he lived, not how he died. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for news, but no one called.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence and in naming, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both criticized and celebrated, accused of lacking depth, and lauded for evoking the 'terrible sublime' through its use of antiquated and modern elements (Burke). The original Gothic Novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, blended old theatrical elements with new novelistic techniques to create a prototype for the Gothic genre. Walpole used 'old' theatrical tropes and 'new' mimetic nature in 'modern' novels to present what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre often harkens back to medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and eras, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated in the face of modern societal and literary advancements. The fusion of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the new format of the novel, allowing readers a more personal view of characters' psychology, is what has kept Gothic alive and both obsolete and fresh to readers many centuries removed from its origins.

Supply chain management is the series of processes involved in moving goods from the point of customer order through the stages of raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. This term was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, who described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to meet customers' needs efficiently. The key elements of supply chain management include production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these elements to provide optimal customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain. It serves as the foundation for the entire process. Production planning involves determining when, where, why, and how products will be made. To make informed decisions, managers look to the market, which provides insights into customer demand. Once the market analysis is complete and customer demand is understood, managers can decide which products to produce and in what quantities. They also decide where to produce these goods, considering factors like volume and quality, while keeping customer satisfaction in mind. After selecting the production location, managers focus on workload scheduling and equipment maintenance. Production is crucial and every detail must be meticulously planned to avoid cost and time inefficiencies. For instance, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target, where every aspect of the business, from employee uniforms to shipment processes, was meticulously designed to ensure smooth operations and clear expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply, which involves strategic decisions on core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. A company may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must decide which division is best suited for each production process. Outsourcing work to other companies can be a core strategy to enhance velocity— the ability to deliver quality and flexibility while reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

In the heart of Yangon, Burma, a chilling sign stands. Ellen Page, the star of "Juno," holds a cardboard plaque above her head, proclaiming, "Hitler is alive in Burma." Burma, also known as Myanmar, has been under the iron grip of a tyrannical military junta since 1962. In 2007, a series of street protests, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution," began, led by the country's Buddhist monks. The peaceful gatherings were met with escalating violence, as the military junta invaded and plundered monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were apprehended and imprisoned, with one photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, being killed for merely attending a protest. The official death toll stands at 13, but defected Colonel Hla Win claims the true number is in the thousands.

This is not an isolated incident. Throughout history, governments have sought to crush dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens. From Roman emperors who claimed divine right to rule to Japanese emperors considered divine themselves, to our current president's weekly consultations with Ted Haggard of Stupid People Worldwide, the desire for power is a universal theme. Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where an estimated 2,000-3,000 people lost their lives, and the Rwandan genocide, where Hutu militia and the government systematically annihilated Tutsis and political moderates. Adolf Hitler's "Third Reich" is another grim reminder of such atrocities.

Duke Ellington’s impact on jazz was largely due to his enduring career and the creative prowess that allowed him to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s subtle presence on the piano is often understated in the selected compositions, yet as a composer, he excelled in crafting intricate pieces that highlighted the unique talents of his band members. He laid the foundation for soloists to freely improvise while also writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that showcased the individual styles of his band members. By emphasizing the ensemble’s tone, Ellington created cohesive and original sounds that complemented each piece. His mastery of each player’s unique sound, as well as their collective harmonies, resulted in some of jazz’s most innovative and brilliant compositions.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentioning Creole Love Call as an early example of his use of voice as a jazz instrument. This piece, featuring a twelve-bar blues structure with six choruses, is a testament to Ellington’s ability to use voice for texture and color without lyrics. Each chorus showcases a different solo, with the voice and reeds engaging in call and response, and the brass and reed sections providing counterpoint. The climactic chorus features the reeds and brass in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time, culminating in a vocal run and a dissonant trombone ending.

Ellington’s use of voice in Creole Love Call is but one instance of his stylistic trait of adding tone color to his compositions. In Hot and Bothered, recorded the following year, Ellington combines his orchestration skills with his ear for tone color. A call and response between Bubber Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing showcases the vocal elements in Miley’s playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, with Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton’s muted trombone introducing the melody and adding depth to Ellington’s innovative use of voice and tone color.

She had felt an unfulfilled yearning for something since she was about 14, entering the world of teenagers. Three years later, at 17, she still hadn't found anything to satisfy this desire. She longed for someone rather than a thing, but no boy had ever caught her interest. Some had tried to woo her, but none had succeeded. This peculiar situation puzzled her, and she often questioned herself about it. Years of contemplation brought up various theories, but none were satisfying enough to truly understand this strange occurrence. So, she lived her life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful, her parents being calm and good-natured. They rarely argued, even with their daughter who had a free and independent spirit. Today, however, was not a calm day. While walking from room to room in search of inspiration, she heard a cry from the kitchen. Her mother's voice was strained and fearful. She rushed in to find her mother on the floor, in pain, and repeating "Ow" in short breaths. Her daughter quickly attended to her, asking, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother requested help and directed her to the car. With her mother's guidance, the daughter carried her to the vehicle, placed her in the back, and drove to the hospital.

The hospital was filled with the scents of disinfectant and sickness, but her mind was focused on her mother's welfare. She rushed her mother to the doctors, who took her away for immediate examination. The daughter was left to wait, filled with worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to reach a high cabinet for a vase.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is linked to a reduced risk of developing chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet is an adaptation of the Med diet, featuring higher consumption of plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, as well as monounsaturated fats over saturated fats, and lower intake of animal products and saturated fats. It also allows for moderate alcohol consumption.

Previous studies have found that adhering to a Med diet is associated with lower total and cardiovascular mortality. Specifically, an intervention trial showed the Med diet promotes weight loss and reduces the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in overweight individuals. However, these studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, who had no history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes, as part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, researchers calculated an aMed diet score from self-reported food frequency questionnaires (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the past year. Over 95% of nurses consistently participated throughout the 20-year period, and FFQs were validated. Cases of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal heart attacks classified this way. Factors like body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and leisure-time physical activity was assessed starting in 1986.

To minimize random variation and better represent long-term dietary habits, cumulative averages of the aMed scores from repeated FFQs were calculated. Adjustments for confounding factors, such as age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use, were made.

Using Cox proportional-hazard modeling, researchers examined the association between an aMed score and CHD and stroke risk, considering fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke cases separately.

The study found that greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to lower risk of CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up, there were 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths. Women in the top aMed quintile had lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile, with a relative risk (RR) of 0.71.

In 2007, the United States of America found itself in the grip of a severe financial crisis. Unemployment skyrocketed, the housing market went into freefall, and many of the nation's largest and most influential corporations were left in ruins. This economic downturn continues to this day, so it's imperative that we examine how this catastrophe occurred and how we can prevent a similar crisis in the future. In essence, the financial crisis was the result of self-interested and short-sighted political decisions that pressured banks and companies to offer sub-prime loans to an already shaky financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into complex financial instruments known as CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks' capital reserves were woefully inadequate, and they passed on the turmoil to the repackaged mortgages and, ultimately, to the broader economy.

The seeds of this crisis were sown during the Clinton administration in 1999. As the president sought to secure a second term, he relaxed lending restrictions to boost his popularity. This move not only set the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later but also laid the groundwork for a potential economic meltdown. Steven Holmes of the New York Times accurately predicted the consequences of these actions in 1999, stating, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stockholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes foretold that “the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As we now know, ill-advised lending policies would indeed lead to the collapse of the economy.

Various factors combined to send the economy into a downward spiral, one of which was the introduction of complex mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used in the years leading up to the crisis. These instruments intertwined various sectors of the economy with the housing market, making households and financial markets increasingly vulnerable to even minor price fluctuations.

The housing bubble eventually burst, leaving financial institutions holding the bag. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the aftermath, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a bargain, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks under intense regulatory scrutiny. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. The section of your story where you either captivate your readers or lose them to sleepy eyes and clicking "Back" buttons. Dr. Merlin herself has shouted at her screen when she realizes she's stuck in a mire of too much information, not even in a good way.

Though we all know the rule, "Show, don't tell," Dr. Merlin finds herself tripping over unnecessary blocks of text where nothing happens, or worse, everything does but in a dull manner. Exposition is that devil whispering in your ear, urging you to get the backstory out of the way so you can get to the main event. But in fiction, telling your audience every detail of every character's history is like serving them a bland meal when they crave a feast.

Let's take an example. You're reading a story and in a few paragraphs, you learn that the heroine met her love, they married in style, and he was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire tale to be told in two pages with only two lines of dialogue from either. You'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, showing through his words and actions how deeply he loved his wife. You'd also want the heroine to reveal, through small and big ways, how his presence transformed her life. A proper introduction to him would make you mourn his death with her, making you more invested in her journey.

In short, you'd expect a hearty meal, not a bony skeleton of a story.

As a writer, you must serve that feast. (*takes a deep breath, presses onward*) It's easy to rush past certain things, like introducing a new character who used to be in the Air Force, now runs a gas station, was married twice, has a soft spot for Eggs Benedict, and secretly dreams of owning the place someday. Don't just tell us all these facts; show us.

I tuned in to two broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first, a live segment on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011), brought news of a grim incident in Ashley, Ohio. A man named Shad Hostettler had stabbed his wife, though her name was not mentioned. His mug shot was shown, and he appeared to be menacing. The story lasted just two minutes, enough time to convey that he had stabbed her multiple times and was in custody, which seemed reasonable given the story's early stage. The second story concerned an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old, in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and no arrests had been made. The SWAT team was investigating, but the coverage seemed brief, which I suspect might be due to the victim being a black man or living in a black neighborhood. I've noticed this pattern before, where minority victims receive less attention in the news. The third story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, struck by a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers were offering a $5,000 reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest. Another report was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, perpetrated by a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie and estimated to be six feet tall and 150 pounds. The story seemed to dwell excessively on his skin color. Lastly, there was a piece about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin sentenced to 300 months in prison, which was oddly stated instead of the standard "25 years". His ethnicity was also mentioned, which seemed irrelevant to the story.

There's a unique connection between brothers; it's unyielding, unshakable, a bond that runs deep. Within this connection lies a spectrum of emotions: love, pride, envy, and malice, among others. Brothers understand each other in ways that only those with such a link can. They see themselves reflected in their brother's eyes. When times are tough, this bond reveals its true colors, whether good or bad. The costs of these emotions are high, and so is the challenge of dealing with their consequences. When one brother looks at another, they see not just their own reflection, but their genuine self. Their actions and their outcomes define their true nature. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers delve into this theme and its accompanying emotions. Traversing a vividly described landscape, these boys embark on a futile journey. Bitterness and intense pride collide in the story's climax, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the protagonist Doodle's direct characterization and his interactions with his brother, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by Doodle and his view of the world, both of which significantly influence his actions.

The protagonist's actions can be traced back to a single emotion: pride. From their first outing together, to their final, tragic expedition, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He desired a brother who could learn all his worldly skills, like "…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…" and someone to race with to Horsehead Landing and perch with in the great pine. Doodle's frailty, however, shattered these dreams. Born with a weak heart, Doodle was unlikely to survive and even less likely to participate in strenuous activities. The young protagonist, filled with vivid imagination, was crushed. Anger even surged within him, as he contemplated smothering Doodle with a pillow—a thought that would haunt any child. Yet, his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him, bringing a glimmer of hope. This shows that his resolve wasn't as strong as it seemed. Deep down, he loved his brother.

The human brain is a complex, ingenious information-processing organ. As technology evolved from primitive to advanced, so did the metaphors used to describe the brain. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, followed by a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you study the brain, keep in mind that these metaphors are limited and can lead to misleading conclusions. Information processing commences with input from sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. This information is repeatedly altered by the brain's algorithms in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when you look at an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing assembles simple details like color, orientation, and edge locations to deduce that you're seeing a box. Top-down processing enhances your recognition of the object by utilizing decisions made at earlier stages of the bottom-up process. In this example, it might help you identify it as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the background. An attention filter then determines the importance of the signal and which cognitive processes it should be accessible to. For instance, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. However, you might pick out your name when spoken in a noisy room. Various stages of processing occur, with the results modulated by attention repeatedly. For the brain to process information, it must first store it. Multiple types of memory exist, including sensory, working, and long-term. Initially, information is encoded; for instance, verbal input can be encoded structurally, phonemically, or semantically. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through specific neurons for a short duration. Information in long-term memory is thought to be preserved in the structure of certain proteins. Numerous models propose how knowledge is organized in the brain, including those based on human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that there are nodes representing concepts, with nodes linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can further link to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley, through the pages of Brave New World, takes aim at the impending threats of technology and capitalism. He envisions a dystopian future where society prioritizes community over individuality, and from birth, individuals are conditioned to chase immediate happiness. The citizens of this world are mere pawns, controlled by the World Controller, who dictates a singular ideology. By applying Marxist lenses, one can discern Huxley's unease with the burgeoning economic systems of his time. Terms like homogenity and reification strengthen the idea that the novel critiques the flaws in the capitalistic framework. Capitalism is mocked through the concept of false consciousness, where the common folk are kept unaware of their true economic ties, focusing instead on personal gain. This is achieved through ideological control, evident in the citizens' hypnopædic conditioning to consume. Hegemony is also apparent, with lower classes oblivious to their manipulation, while upper classes, like the Alphas and Betas, accept their roles without resistance. The superficial interactions and lack of depth among characters suggest that technology and capitalism stifle free will and expression. Love and strong emotions are absent, replaced by shallow, appearance-driven remarks about women and casual discussions of encounters. Each class's contentment with their status is a clear sign of capitalistic influence, showing the proletariat's false belief in their superiority so long as they consume and conform.

I've been a student at University Park for approximately two and a half years, which translates to four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus can be a challenge, especially for those like myself who live in East Halls, the farthest eastward dorms on campus, near the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from Stuart Hall to Willard building, for instance, can take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the weather is bad. It wasn't always this way; not long ago, East Halls were separated from the main campus by empty land. Now, that space has been filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services, and apartments. As the campus continues to grow, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. The solution? Bicycles. But they're only effective if students are willing to use them, and the campus must be designed with cyclists in mind.

My friend, who recently started riding again after a long break, shared his thoughts: "Bikes are great; it's the only way to get around." Besides promoting physical health, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A simple bowl of oatmeal and some exertion can take you 30 miles. As an off-campus student, I've found the smartest decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. My daily commute to Thomas building, a twenty-five-minute walk from my home, takes just 5 minutes on a bike. Yet, Pollock Road, the direct route, isn't always easy to travel by bike. While walking has its merits, I'm too busy for that. Without my bike, walking would be my only option, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to my daily commute to Thomas—over two and a half hours each week. And that's just for Thomas; the cumulative time spent walking for classes, appointments, and other activities would be unmanageable.
